  "title" : "How to do URL decoding in Java?",
  "body" : "<p><strong>In Java, I want to convert this:</strong></p>\n\n<pre><code>https%3A%2F%2Fmywebsite%2Fdocs%2Fenglish%2Fsite%2Fmybook.do%3Frequest_type\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>To this:</strong></p>\n\n<pre><code>https://mywebsite/docs/english/site/mybook.do&amp;request_type\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>This is what I have so far:</strong></p>\n\n<pre><code>class StringUTF \n{\n    public static void main(String[] args) \n    {\n        try{\n            String url = \n               \"https%3A%2F%2Fmywebsite%2Fdocs%2Fenglish%2Fsite%2Fmybook.do\" +\n               \"%3Frequest_type%3D%26type%3Dprivate\";\n\n            System.out.println(url+\"Hello World!-------&gt;\" +\n                new String(url.getBytes(\"UTF-8\"),\"ASCII\"));\n        }\n        catch(Exception E){\n        }\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>But it doesn't work right.  What are these <code>%3A</code> and <code>%2F</code> formats called and how do I convert them?</p>\n"
